location: Yuma East Wetlands, Yuma, Arizona, United States
remarks: XC314730 © Bobby Wilcox // Yuma East Wetlands, Yuma, Arizona (32.7257, -114.6074), United States // 40m // 06:00h, 2016-04-30 // call // This call, sometimes referred to as the squeal or squeak duet, is given by two birds who have been foraging apart and get too far apart and then come back together.  It is typically given by a mated pair but can be adult and juveniles or two juveniles as well.  I did not get a good enough look to age these birds but I suspect they were adults.  Recording taken from about 20' away and the birds were on the ground.  The process of finding each other and coming back together may have been initiated in response to my presence as a perceived threat.   /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no

location: Laguna Dam Conservation Area, Yuma County, Arizona, United States
remarks: XC315931 © Bobby Wilcox // Laguna Dam Conservation Area, Yuma County, Arizona (32.8331, -114.4721), United States // 50m // 07:30h, 2016-05-10 // male, song // Very strange song from an adult male Common Yellowthroat.  This was a marshy patch of land consisting of cattails and rushes surrounding an 'island' of partially flooded small mesquite trees and arrowweed.   It sounds similar to a type of Wilson's Warbler song but I was drawn to the bird because the Wilson's Warblers that migrate through here do not usually sing this type of song in my experience, so I wasn't sure what it was.  The bird was being very furtive, in the vein of a Common Yellowthroat or MacGillivray's Warbler.  What first got me thinking it was a Common Yellowthroat was when I heard it do a typical COYE call from the same spot as the song was coming.  Being that the song was so weird and MGWA has a similar call I thought perhaps it was just an odd MGWA practicing its song while migrating.  I was doing a survey so I had to abandon the bird but when I came back past the spot later it was still singing from the same place so I began investigating again.  I chased it around for close to an hour, making recordings and trying to get a look at it.  Finally I zeroed in on a spot where it was singing consistently and crept to within ~15ft.  There were no other birds around.  Out from the exact spot where the singing had come from hopped an adult male COYE (albeit a little scruffy looking).  I did not see the song emerge directly from his bill.  But I saw him fly to a clump of brush not 10ft from me and immediately the same song burst forth from that very spot so I am 100% certain of the singing bird's identity.  At this point I continued to observe the bird fly from brush clump to brush clump and sing the weird song and utter typical COYE calls.  In most of the recordings I took it seems to be countersinging with COYEs nearby to some extent which seems to indicate that it knows what its song it 'supposed to' song like.  At no point during my pursuit of this bird did it ever, to my knowledge or listening, switch to the typical COYE song.   /  / *Note: I originally uploaded this recording as having 'seen' the bird but technically at this time I had not actually seen it.  Later uploaded recordings (XC315932 and XC315933) reflect having seen the bird and making a definitive ID.  Based on the static location, similar skulky behavior and the fact that the song was consistent over the entire time period, I am confident that this bird, recorded 2.5 hours earlier, is the same bird that was later seen and appears in XC315932 and XC315933. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:no // also:  Common Yellowthroat, Yellow-headed Blackbird, Killdeer, American Coot

remarks: XC332508 © Lance A. M. Benner // Lake Hughes Road, Los Angeles County, California (34.6071, -118.5608), United States // 600m // 19:18h, 2016-03-26 // call, male // Faint recording of male advertising calls.  Uploaded for documentation because long-eared owl is a rare species in this area.  The sounds are faint and it may be necessary to use headphones or earbuds to hear them.  Recorded 20 minutes after sunset in thick trees along a riparian corridor that had an active creek.   Earlier in the day I hiked into this site and found a nest.  The sounds on this recording are probably a male, based on the low frequency of the hoots.   /  / Continuation of the file that appears in XC332503 and XC3323504.  I split the file into three pieces to crop out two gunshots partway through the original recording.   /  / Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder, Sennheiser ME62 microphone, and a Telinga 22 inch parabola.   / Modifications to the file: cropped and amplified by 10 dB.   /  / Water in the creek and frogs are also audible. /  / Due to the low frequency of the calls, which have a wavelength larger than the diameter of the dish, it probably would have been better to use a shotgun mic. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:no // also:  Black Phoebe, Nuttall's Woodpecker

Benner // El Prieto Canyon, Angeles National Forest (near  Altadena), Los Angeles County, California (34.2202, -118.1551), United States // 600m // 21:35h, 2014-06-17 // alarm call, begging call, juvenile, male // Vocalizations by adult male and fledgling western screech owls.
